<div id="banner">
	<h1>Stanford: Feats of Memory</h1>
</div>

<div class="content">
<p class="dateline">March 18</p>

<p>I used to complain that grades weren&#8217;t really for different fields &#8212; biology, history, etc. &#8212; they were all different grades for memorization, just memorization of different types of information. Well, the psychology final has taken that one step further. It&#8217;s not memorization, it&#8217;s just reading comprehension.</p>

<p>To pass the test, apparently all you need to do is read the textbook beforehand and remember what it said. No thought or application is required. (Indeed, thought will probably screw you over since some of the &#8220;correct&#8221; answers are wrong. I thought about telling the proctors as I left that &#8220;the answer to number 26 is wrong&#8221; but they&#8217;d probably look at me real funny.)</p>

<p class="posted">posted March 26, 2005 07:39 PM (<a class="category" href="cat_education">Education</a>) (<a href="#comments">3 comments</a>) <a href="001651" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>

